[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round ""]
[White "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "01. The Fianchetto Variation: White plays 8.Ne1"]
[Result "*"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nf3 {If White wishes to play the Fianchetto Variation 
he can also start with3.g3, but the game will transpose 
after3...Bg74.Nf3O-O.} 3...Bg7 4.g3 O-O 5.Bg2 d6 {Black plays the usual 
KID moves.} 6.Nc3 c6 {A very flexible move for Black. First of all, he 
shuts the long diagonal for White's fianchettoed bishop. He also keeps his
options open: He can play ...e5, ...d5 or even ...c5. He prepares a 
possible ...b5. He can develop his knight from b8 to d7 or a6. The pawn 
move also opens the a5-d8 diagonal for the queen, giving her access to the
b6 and a5 squares.} 7.O-O {This is by far the most common move and is 
often automatically played.} 7...Bf5 {Black develops the bishop and 
controls the e4-square, thus preventing White's expansion with e4. Now 
White has a wide choice, but his most ambitious moves revolve around the 
fight for the e4-square.} 8.Ne1 {White still wants to play e4 but avoids 
putting the knight on the rim.} 8...e5 {Since White abandoned the control 
over the e5-square Black executes the typical KID push in the centre.} 9.
d5 cxd5 {With this exchange Black gets rid of the pressure on the pawn on 
c6.} 10.cxd5 {Taking with a knight is harmless as 
after10.Nxd5Nxd511.Bxd5Nc6 Black obtains smooth development and can 
continue with ...Qd7, ...Be6 and ...f5.} 10...a5 $1 {An important move on 
the queenside. Black increases his control over the dark squares, b4 and 
c5 in particular and stops a possible expansion by White.} *

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round ""]
[White "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "02. The Fianchetto Variation: White plays 8.Nh4"]
[Result "*"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nf3 {If White wishes to play the Fianchetto Variation 
he can also start with3.g3, but the game will transpose 
after3...Bg74.Nf3O-O.} 3...Bg7 4.g3 O-O 5.Bg2 d6 {Black plays the usual 
KID moves.} 6.Nc3 c6 {A very flexible move for Black. First of all, he 
shuts the long diagonal for White's fianchettoed bishop. He also keeps his
options open: He can play ...e5, ...d5 or even ...c5. He prepares a 
possible ...b5. He can develop his knight from b8 to d7 or a6. The pawn 
move also opens the a5-d8 diagonal for the queen, giving her access to the
b6 and a5 squares.} 7.O-O {This is by far the most common move and is 
often automatically played.} 7...Bf5 {Black develops the bishop and 
controls the e4-square, thus preventing White's expansion with e4. Now 
White has a wide choice, but his most ambitious moves revolve around the 
fight for the e4-square.} 8.Nh4 {The most commonly played move. White 
attacks the bishop on f5 and intends to play e4. The drawback of the move 
is obvious - the knight is now on the rim.} 8...Be6 {Black moves away with
tempo and provokes White to push d5.} 9.d5 cxd5 10.cxd5 Bd7 {From d7 the 
bishop supports the ...b5 push though Black should be careful about it as 
it weakens the c6-square.} 11.Nf3 {White brings the knight back from the 
rim. Against other moves Black's play won't differ much from the main 
line. Generally speaking Black's piece placement in these lines is fairly 
straightforward: The knight goes to a6 and likely to c5. The queen to a5 
or b6. One rook comes to c8.} 11...Na6 {Black follows his plan, obtaining 
good play on the queenside.} *

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round ""]
[White "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "03. The Saemisch Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 {White naturally takes over the centre.} 
4...d6 {Preventing e5.} 5.f3 {This move is typical for the Saemisch 
Variation, named after the German Grandmaster Friedrich Saemisch. The idea
is quite simple: since one aspect of Black's counterplay in the KID is the
attack on the e4-pawn White immediately defends it securely.} 5...O-O {
Black finishes development and is now ready to start play against White's 
centre. Now White has a choice where to develop his dark-squared bishop, 
to e3 or to g5. Note that the move6.Nge2 has no independent value because 
after6...Nc6 White again needs to make the same choice about the 
development of the bishop, hence transposing to the main lines either 
after 6.Be3 or 6.Bg5.} 6.Be3 {This is the typical Saemisch development.} 
6...Nc6 {This is the Panno Variation. Black puts pressure on the d4-square
and wants to play ...e5 and ...Nd4 if allowed.} 7.Nge2 {In view of Black's
threat of ...e5 and ...Nd4 this is White's only reasonable move. For 
example, the careless7.Qd2?! is met by7...e58.d5Nd4 with great play.} 7...
a6 {Black prepares for the possibility to push ...b5 and attack White's 
vulnerable c4-pawn.} 8.Qd2 {The usual move. White finishes development and
prepares Bh6, 0-0-0 or Rd1.} 8...Na5 $5 {A relatively fresh idea compared 
to the traditional move8...Rb8. Black immediately starts counterplay 
against the pawn on c4 and keeping the rook on a8 for now gives him 
additional tactical chances based on the fork ...Nb3.} 9.Nc1 $1 {This is 
White's best attempt. He safely covers the b3-square. The naive9.b3?! 
shows the point of having the rook on a8 
after9...b5!10.cxb5axb511.Nxb5?Nxb3 Black wins the exchange thanks to the 
pin on the a-file.} 9...Nd7 {Preparing the ...c5 push. Black has 
interesting alternatives in: A)9...e5!?10.d5c5 which leads to typical 
closed KID positions. B)9...c5!?, a pawn sacrifice after10.dxc5Be6.} *

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round ""]
[White "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "04. The Four Pawns Attack: White plays 9.Nxe5"]
[Result "*"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 {White naturally takes over the centre.} 
4...d6 {Preventing e5.} 5.f4 {In the beginning of the KID the Four Pawns 
Attack was considered the refutation of this defence. White's strategy is 
very direct, he takes up maximum space and wants to strangulate Black. 
Nowadays the line is not considered a critical one as Black has more than 
one good way to deal with it.} 5...O-O 6.Nf3 e5 $5 {The shocking effect of
this move never ceases to amaze me. White controls the e5-square 3 times 
and yet it is exactly there that Black strikes! This move also changes the
character of the game, as now White has a choice - either to take a pawn 
and allow Black compensation in view of a pleasant initiative or to allow 
his centre to be attacked.} 7.dxe5 dxe5 8.Qxd8 Rxd8 9.Nxe5 {This is an 
alternative, but Black has no problems after:} 9...b6 $1 {With the idea of
...Bb7, attacking the pawn on e4.} *

