[Black "05. The Four Pawns Attack: White plays 9.fxe5"]
[Result "*"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 {White naturally takes over the centre.} 
4...d6 {Preventing e5.} 5.f4 {In the beginning of the KID the Four Pawns 
Attack was considered the refutation of this defence. White's strategy is 
very direct, he takes up maximum space and wants to strangulate Black. 
Nowadays the line is not considered a critical one as Black has more than 
one good way to deal with it.} 5...O-O 6.Nf3 e5 $5 {The shocking effect of
this move never ceases to amaze me. White controls the e5-square 3 times 
and yet it is exactly there that Black strikes! This move also changes the
character of the game, as now White has a choice - either to take a pawn 
and allow Black compensation in view of a pleasant initiative or to allow 
his centre to be attacked.} 7.dxe5 dxe5 8.Qxd8 Rxd8 9.fxe5 {This wrecks 
White's central pawns, but it gains a tempo.} 9...Nfd7 {Attacking the pawn
on e5. From d7 the knight can further go to c5 or f8.} *

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round ""]
[White "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "06. The Averbakh Variation: White plays 6.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 {White naturally takes over the centre.} 
4...d6 {Preventing e5.} 5.Be2 O-O 6.Be3 {This system is one of the most 
popular against the KID nowadays. Its idea is similar to the Makagonov 
System - White wants to advance on the kingside with g4, h4 etc. thus 
either suffocating Black's counterplay there or creating an attack on the 
kingside himself. The difference with the Makagonov is that here White 
controls the g4-square with the bishop on e2, while there White plays h3.}
6...e5 {Black strikes in the centre with the usual move.} 7.d5 {White 
closes the centre and will continue with g4 and h4. Note that the 
move7.Nf3 leads to the Gligoric Variation.} 7...Na6 {Black develops the 
knight on a6 in order not to block the bishop on c8 and intends to put it 
on c5 to attack the pawn on e4.} 8.g4 {White continues with his plan.} 
8...Nc5 {Attacking the pawn on e4. Now White can defend it in two ways, 
with a pawn or with a bishop.} 9.f3 h5 {Black undermines White's expanded 
kingside, using the fact that with his last move White closed the d1-h5 
diagonal so there is no pressure on the h5-pawn.} 10.g5 {The most natural 
and main move.} 10...Nh7 {Getting away with tempo.} 11.h4 f6 {Black 
continues to put pressure on the pawn on g5 and manages to open the 
f-file. After the exchange of pawns the pawn on h4 will also become 
vulnerable. Now White has a choice, to exchange on f6 or to allow Black to
take on g5.} *

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round ""]
[White "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "07. The Averbakh Variation: White plays 6.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 {White naturally takes over the centre.} 
4...d6 {Preventing e5.} 5.Be2 O-O 6.Bg5 {This development of the bishops 
on e2 and g5 is characteristic for the Averbakh Variation. The idea to put
the bishop on g5 is to stop Black's typical central push ...e5.} 6...c5 {
To illustrate White's idea, pushing ...e5 loses 
after6...e5??7.dxe5dxe58.Qxd8Rxd89.Nd5 and Black loses material because of
the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal and the weakness of the pawn on c7. Pushing 
the c-pawn however aims to take immediate advantage of the lack of 
protection of the d4-square and the weakening of the long diagonal, the 
b2-pawn in particular, as White's dark-squared bishop left the c1-square.}
7.d5 {The only critical try.} 7...e6 {Undermining White's centre and 
intending to open the e-file after ...exd5.} 8.Qd2 {This is the main move 
and the reason why for many years Black's last move was considered 
imprecise because White stops ...h6. However, modern theory and practice 
have shown that Black can play ...h6 at a later stage with a powerful 
effect.} 8...exd5 {Black follows his plan and opens the e-file.} 9.exd5 
Qb6 $1 {The key move that rehabilitated the line for Black. For a very 
long time, it was considered that White's space advantage coupled with the
pin on the h4-d8 diagonal give White a stable edge, but with the queen 
move Black introduces strong dynamism in the position. There are two ideas
to this move: the first one is to allow for ...Bf5 and ...Ne4 (the knight 
is free to jump now that there is no pin) and the second one is to put 
pressure on the b2-pawn.} *

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round ""]
[White "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "08. Various Systems: White plays 5.Be2 6.h4"]
[Result "*"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 {White naturally takes over the centre.} 
4...d6 {Preventing e5.} 5.Be2 O-O 6.h4 {This line with6.h4 became popular 
as a way to avoid the Grunfeld Defence after 1.d4Nf62.c4g63.h4 when play 
would usually transpose to our lines after3...Bg74.Nc3d65.e4O-O6.Be2.} 
6...h5 {Stopping White's idea is the simplest.} 7.Nf3 Bg4 {The bishop uses
the weakened g4-square to exert pressure on White's centre in an indirect 
way, by attacking the knight that controls the d4-square.} 8.Be3 {White 
lends extra support to the d4-pawn.} 8...Nbd7 {Black finishes development 
and is ready to push ...e5, but he will only do so once White has castled 
short. He wants to be able to change plans and play ...c6, ...Qa5 and 
...b5 in case White castles long.} *

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round ""]
[White "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "09. The Makagonov System"]
[Result "*"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 {White naturally takes over the centre.} 
4...d6 {Preventing e5.} 5.h3 {This little move is the start of the 
Makagonov Variation, one of the most critical tries against the KID today.
The 'little' move is quite venomous: White covers the g4-square like in 
the Saemisch Variation, only that he doesn't take away the f3-square from 
his knight. Additionally, by leaving the pawn on f2 his bishop on e3 will 
be more stable. The move h3 also supports the g4-advance, aimed either at 
limiting Black's kingside counterplay by exerting more control over the 
f5-square or with the idea to start an attack on the kingside, by opening 
the g-file by gxf5 or by advancing g4-g5 and h4-h5.} 5...O-O {Black 
completes his kingside development. Now White has a choice to make - 
whether to develop the dark-squared bishop (to g5 or e3) or to develop the
knight to f3, keeping both possibilities for the dark-squared bishop (g5 
or e3) available. Against all of these Black needs to decide in which 
direction he would like the game to proceed. He has three options: to go 
for the typical KID positions after executing ...e5, to aim for Modern 
Benoni positions with ...c5 or to give the game an original character with
some alternative ideas. In this repertoire, we will go for the third 
option.} 6.Nf3 {White develops the knight on its natural square from where
it covers the d4-square and controls the e5-square.} 6...Nc6 $5 7.d5 {
Practically forced. Otherwise Black plays ...e5 and ...Nd4, for 
example7.Be3?!e58.d5Nd4 is great for Black and it's a transposition to the
line 6.Be3Nc67.Nf3?!e58.d5Nd4.} 7...Nb4 {Unlike the line with 6.Be3 here 
the knight on f3 controls the e5-square so Black's knight has to go to b4.
} 8.Be2 {It's better for White to refrain from chasing away the knight on 
b4 too early because the knight wants to go to a6 and c5 anyway.} 8...e6 {
Black undermines White's pawn on d5. His idea is to put a rook on e8 and 
take on d5 when thanks to the pressure on e4 White will be forced to 
recapture with the e-pawn, resulting in a comfortable symmetrical pawn 
structure for Black.} 9.Be3 {By developing the dark-squared bishop White 
allows for Nd2 to cover the pawn on e4 so as to be able to recapture cxd5 
when Black takes ...exd5.} 9...Re8 {Black continues with the plan, he 
wants to take on d5 now to force exd5 in view of the pressure on the pawn 
on e4.} 10.Nd2 {White defends the pawn to allow cxd5. 
After10.O-Oexd511.exd5a5 apart from the idea of ...Na6-c5 Black also has 
the typical exchange sacrifice ...Rxe3 at his disposal when his 
compensation will consist of his control of the dark squares and White's 
weaknesses on the e-file, the e3-pawn and the e4- and e5-squares.} 10...a5
{The standard move on the queenside, obtaining better control over the 
dark squares c5 and b4. An interesting alternative is10...c5!? with a 
delayed Benoni structure.} *

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round ""]
[White "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "10. Various Systems: White plays 5.Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 {White naturally takes over the centre.} 
4...d6 {Preventing e5.} 5.Bd3 {This system was popularised by GM Yasser 
Seirawan. White intends to develop his king's knight to e2, thus allowing 
several things: f3 to support the pawn on e4, like in the Saemisch 
Variation. To play f4 as a reply to Black's ...f5, thus stopping Black's 
kingside advance. To play Ng3, increasing White's control over the e4- and
f5-squares. The drawback of this setup is the decreased control over the 
d4-square as the bishop on d3 severs the connection between the queen on 
d1 and the pawn on d4.} 5...O-O 6.Nge2 Nc6 {Black immediately targets the 
weakened spot in White's position.} 7.O-O e5 {Black attacks White's 
vulnerable d4-spot.} 8.d5 Nd4 {Again Black takes advantage of White's 
insufficient control over the d4-square by placing his knight in a 
dominant position.} *

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round ""]
[White "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "11. Various Systems: White plays 5.Nge2"]
[Result "*"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 {White naturally takes over the centre.} 
4...d6 {Preventing e5.} 5.Nge2 {The knight is en route to g3, from where 
it controls the f5 and e4 squares. From g3 it also aids the h4-h5 advance.
} 5...O-O 6.Ng3 e5 {Black reacts in a typical KID fashion.} 7.d5 a5 {
Another typical move after White has closed the centre: Black grabs some 
space on the queenside and obtains better control over the dark squares on
the queenside, b4 and c5 in particular.} 8.Be2 {The bishop from e2 
supports the h4-h5 idea.} 8...Na6 {Black develops the knight on a6 from 
where it is ready to join the game by jumping to c5.} 9.h4 h5 $1 {It is 
important to stop White's idea of h5 because allowing it gives White the 
options to either open the h-file by taking on g6 or to shut Black's 
kingside by playing h6.} *

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round ""]
[White "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "12. The Classical Variation: Gligoric Variation (7.Be3)"]
[Result "*"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 {White naturally takes over the centre.} 
4...d6 {Preventing e5.} 5.Nf3 O-O {Black finished the development of the 
kingside and is now ready to play in the centre.} 6.Be2 {This is White's 
most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this 
variation is called the Classical Variation.} 6...e5 {The central strike 
that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the 
d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on 
e5, or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the 
fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from: 1. He 
can keep the tension in the centre by castling7.O-O 2. He can keep the 
tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 
with7.Be3 - the Gligoric Variation. 3. He can blockade the centre 
immediately with7.d5 - the Petrosian Variation. 4. He can exchange the 
pawns and then the queens after7.dxe5 - the Exchange Variation.} 7.Be3 {
This is the Gligoric Variation. Its idea is to postpone castling and keep 
the tension in the centre.} 7...exd4 {This is the most straightforward and
direct approach. Black opens the long diagonal, the centre and the e-file 
while White's king is still uncastled.} 8.Nxd4 Re8 {Attacking the pawn on 
e4.} 9.f3 {Strengthening the centre, but now the bishop on e3 is somewhat 
loose and Black uses this fact to strike in the centre with ...c6 and 
...d5.} 9...c6 {Irrelevant of what White does next, the central thrust 
...d5 is inevitably coming on the next move, giving Black lively piece 
play.} *

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round ""]
[White "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "13. The Classical Variation: Petrosian Variation (7.d5)"]
[Result "*"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 {White naturally takes over the centre.} 
4...d6 {Preventing e5.} 5.Nf3 O-O {Black finished the development of the 
kingside and is now ready to play in the centre.} 6.Be2 {This is White's 
most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this 
variation is called the Classical Variation.} 6...e5 {The central strike 
that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the 
d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on 
e5, or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the 
fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from: 1. He 
can keep the tension in the centre by castling7.O-O 2. He can keep the 
tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 
with7.Be3 - the Gligoric Variation. 3. He can blockade the centre 
immediately with7.d5 - the Petrosian Variation. 4. He can exchange the 
pawns and then the queens after7.dxe5 - the Exchange Variation.} 7.d5 {The
Petrosian Variation, invented and made popular by the 9th World Champion 
in the late 50s and early 60s. White immediately closes the centre and 
intends to start his usual queenside play by advancing the pawns with b4 
and c5.} 7...Nbd7 {The idea of this move is to develop and keep an eye on 
the c5-square, where the knight can jump in order to attack the pawn on e4
and stop or slow down White's intended queenside expansion. When the 
Petrosian Variation was at the height of its popularity in the late 50s 
and early 60s this move was the most common way to meet it. Later on the 
move 7...a5 came to the fore while the third option 7...Na6 never really 
caught on. Today the move7...a5 is considered the main line against the 
Petrosian Variation, but from a practical perspective, it is not an easy 
move to play because all White's 3 main moves against it -8.Bg5,8.Be3 
and8.h3 lead to a lot of deeply analysed theoretical lines. Therefore I 
turned my attention to the alternatives and I soon discovered that the 
problem with7...Na6 was the move8.Nd2! when I couldn't find a satisfactory
way for Black. Luckily, the 'original' reaction with7...Nbd7 hid quite a 
few improvements and turned out to be very compact theoretically.} 8.Bg5 {
This is Petrosian's prophylactic idea - with the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal
White tries to slow down Black's plan of kingside expansion that consists 
of moving the knight from f6 and pushing ...f5. Note that the move8.O-O is
harmless because after8...Nc59.Qc2a5 Black will first solidify his knight 
on c5 by playing ...b6 and then will move his knight from f6 to execute 
the ...f5 push with very easy play as White castled a bit too early and 
his queenside play is nowhere near to start.} 8...h6 {Black naturally 
wants to get rid of the bishop.} 9.Bh4 g5 {Forcing the bishop to the 
passive square on g3.} 10.Bg3 Nh5 {From here the knight can either take 
the bishop on g3 when the time is right, or it can jump to f4.} *

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round ""]
[White "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "14. The Classical Variation: Exchange Variation (7.dxe5)"]
[Result "*"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 {White naturally takes over the centre.} 
4...d6 {Preventing e5.} 5.Nf3 O-O {Black finished the development of the 
kingside and is now ready to play in the centre.} 6.Be2 {This is White's 
most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this 
variation is called the Classical Variation.} 6...e5 {The central strike 
that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the 
d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on 
e5, or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the 
fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from: 1. He 
can keep the tension in the centre by castling7.O-O 2. He can keep the 
tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 
with7.Be3 - the Gligoric Variation. 3. He can blockade the centre 
immediately with7.d5 - the Petrosian Variation. 4. He can exchange the 
pawns and then the queens after7.dxe5 - the Exchange Variation.} 7.dxe5 {
The Exchange Variation is rather harmless, though Black needs to know how 
to react to it.} 7...dxe5 8.Qxd8 Rxd8 {The pawn structure is in Black's 
favour now in view of the hole on d4.} 9.Bg5 {This is the main move. White
should be incisive in this endgame because he has the worse pawn structure
- the gaping hole on d4 cannot be controlled by a pawn, while Black can 
cover the d5-square by ...c6. Many KID endgames have been won by Black 
rather effortlessly following the scenario of exchanging the dark-squared 
bishops, giving up the light-squared bishop for the knight on f3 and then 
planting a knight on d4, which leads to the dream position for Black of a 
dominating knight on d4 versus an awful bishop on e2. Note that the pawn 
on e5 is taboo in view of the trick9.Nxe5?!Nxe4! and the bishop on g7 
springs to life on the open diagonal.} 9...Re8 {Getting away from the pin 
and defending the pawn on e5. Now Black wants to play ...c6, so White's 
next move is the critical one.} 10.Nd5 Nxd5 {The knight has to be 
eliminated.} 11.cxd5 c6 {Black naturally wants to undermine White's strong
point on d5, at the same time getting rid of the backward pawn on c7.} 12.
Bc4 {White intends to recapture on d5 with a bishop.} 12...cxd5 {
Eliminating the d5-pawn.} 13.Bxd5 Nd7 $1 {This is important to remember. 
The natural move is to put the knight on c6, but from d7 the knight has 
two important tasks: one is to control the d5-square, either from f6 (from
here the knight also targets the pawn on e4) or b6, and the other is to go
to c5 in order to allow for ...Be6 and after the exchange of bishops to 
land on e6, from where it can further go to d4 or f4.} *

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round ""]
[White "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "15. The Classical Variation: Main Line (7.0-0) with 8.dxe5"]
[Result "*"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 {White naturally takes over the centre.} 
4...d6 {Preventing e5.} 5.Nf3 O-O {Black finished the development of the 
kingside and is now ready to play in the centre.} 6.Be2 {This is White's 
most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this 
variation is called the Classical Variation.} 6...e5 {The central strike 
that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the 
d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on 
e5, or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the 
fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from: 1. He 
can keep the tension in the centre by castling7.O-O 2. He can keep the 
tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 
with7.Be3 - the Gligoric Variation. 3. He can blockade the centre 
immediately with7.d5 - the Petrosian Variation. 4. He can exchange the 
pawns and then the queens after7.dxe5 - the Exchange Variation.} 7.O-O {
The most natural move for White, getting the king out of the centre.} 7...
Bg4 $5 {This rare move has been known since the 50s, but it was never 
considered to be good. This conclusion changed when it was successfully 
used by Caruana to convincingly defeat Wojtaszek in the Wijk aan Zee 
tournament in 2021. In fact, the move is a logical one as Black fights for
the control of the dark squares by attacking the knight on f3 that 
controls both e5 and d4. It also has the benefit of not being explored as 
deeply as the more theoretical alternatives, which allows Black to obtain 
a fresh position without the need for massive memorisation.} 8.dxe5 {This 
is harmless as it leads to simplifications where Black obtains easy play.}
8...Bxf3 {Black continues his plan of fighting for the dark squares - the 
knight on f3 is eliminated.} 9.exf6 {In case of9.Bxf3dxe5 Black has an 
excellent position with a quick ...Nc6-d4 taking immediate advantage of 
the hole on d4.} 9...Bxe2 {The only move, as taking on f6 loses a piece.} 
10.Qxe2 Qxf6 11.Nd5 Qd8 {Defending the pawn on c7 and intending ...c6, 
...Nd7 next with a comfortable position.} *

