a5 {A typical move on the queenside for Black. He increases his control 
over the squares b4 and c5, thus slowing down White's expansion by b4 and 
c5. The pawn on a5 also ensures a safe spot on c5 for the knight.} 9.Ne1 {
This is an ambitious move, aiming for the ideal (for White) exchange of 
the light-squared bishops (White's is a limited one, Black's is a good 
one). Furthermore, the knight from e1 will come to d3 to support the 
c5-push.} 9...Bd7 {Black avoids the unfavourable exchange.} 10.Nd3 Na6 {A 
typical development for Black, the pawn on a5 and the knight on a6 make it
pretty difficult for White to make any progress on the queenside.} *

