the only critical option, as the alternatives give Black easy play.} 8...
a5 {A typical move on the queenside for Black. He increases his control 
over the squares b4 and c5, thus slowing down White's expansion by b4 and 
c5. The pawn on a5 also ensures a safe spot on c5 for the knight.} 9.h3 $5
{Normally White doesn't play like this in the KID, weakening the kingside,
but in this case it forces the exchange of Black's light-squared bishop. 
This is a double-edged decision as even though White obtains the pair of 
bishops he does weaken his kingside and slows down his queenside play.} 
